21
00:01:37,345 --> 00:01:39,540
<i>A lot of people come in
to indie games...</i>

22
00:01:39,706 --> 00:01:41,640
<i>...trying to be like a big company.</i>

23
00:01:41,806 --> 00:01:43,780
<i>What those companies do...</i>

24
00:01:43,948 --> 00:01:45,780
...is create highly polished things...

25
00:01:45,946 --> 00:01:50,190
<i>...that serve as large
of an audience as possible.</i>

26
00:01:50,700 --> 00:01:53,193
<i>The way that you do that is by...</i>

27
00:01:53,361 --> 00:01:55,591
<i>...filing off all the bumps
on something.</i>

28
00:01:55,761 --> 00:01:56,948
<i>If there's a sharp corner,</i>

29
00:01:57,116 --> 00:01:58,783
<i>you make sure it's not going to
hurt anybody.</i>

30
00:01:58,953 --> 00:02:00,106
<i>If they bump into it or whatever.</i>

31
00:02:00,275 --> 00:02:04,186
<i>That creation of this highly glossy,
commercial product</i>

32
00:02:04,355 --> 00:02:06,331
<i>Is the opposite of
making something personal.</i>

33
00:02:06,501 --> 00:02:08,710
I am determined to make video games...

34
00:02:08,878 --> 00:02:11,055
...and I make video games
because I can.

35
00:02:11,223 --> 00:02:12,951
I'm very, very good at programing.

36
00:02:13,173 --> 00:02:16,793
I can still make something that
expresses myself.

37
00:02:16,961 --> 00:02:19,475
Like a movie or something
that I wrote.

38
00:02:19,656 --> 00:02:21,848
I can make that as a video game.

39
00:02:22,048 --> 00:02:24,711
And I have the full ability
to do that.

40
00:02:25,395 --> 00:02:26,791
<i>Things that are personal...</i>

41
00:02:26,960 --> 00:02:29,353
<i>...have flaws.
They have vulnerabilities.</i>

42
00:02:29,521 --> 00:02:31,481
To me, games
are the ultimate art form.

43
00:02:31,650 --> 00:02:33,443
It's just the ultimate medium.

44
00:02:33,611 --> 00:02:37,518
It's the sum total of every
expressive medium of all time...

45
00:02:37,686 --> 00:02:38,770
...made interactive.

46
00:02:38,938 --> 00:02:40,131
How is that not...

47
00:02:40,300 --> 00:02:41,398
It's AWESOME!

48
00:02:41,566 --> 00:02:42,298
I want to be part of it.

49
00:02:42,466 --> 00:02:45,605
I want to have a say
in what becomes of video games.

50
00:02:45,773 --> 00:02:48,363
<i>If you don't see a
vulnerability in somebody...</i>

51
00:02:48,531 --> 00:02:51,585
<i>You're probably not relating with them
on a very personal level.</i>

52
00:02:51,753 --> 00:02:54,428
<i>So it's the same with a game design.</i>

53
00:02:54,600 --> 00:02:57,341
My whole career has been me,
trying to find new ways...

54
00:02:57,510 --> 00:02:59,188
...to communicate with people.

55
00:02:59,356 --> 00:03:01,215
Because, I desperately want to
communicate with people.

56
00:03:01,385 --> 00:03:03,306
But I don't want the
messy interaction of having to...

57
00:03:03,683 --> 00:03:04,931
...make friends and talk to people.

58
00:03:05,100 --> 00:03:06,540
Because I probably don't like them.

59
00:03:06,710 --> 00:03:08,936
When you make games.
And you put stuff up online.

60
00:03:09,105 --> 00:03:11,271
And people like your stuff
or don't like your stuff.

61
00:03:11,440 --> 00:03:13,768
Either way, they're going to give you
some kind of feedback.

62
00:03:13,998 --> 00:03:15,568
And you have this conversation.

63
00:03:15,736 --> 00:03:17,691
It's why a writer writes I guess.

64
00:03:17,860 --> 00:03:19,036
Because they can.

65
00:03:19,206 --> 00:03:21,156
It's the most effective way to
express themselves.

66
00:03:21,325 --> 00:03:26,536
And a video game is the most
effective way I can express myself.

67
00:03:26,936 --> 00:03:28,873
<i>Making it was about...</i>

68
00:03:29,043 --> 00:03:32,278
<i>Let me take my deepest flaws
and vulnerabilities...</i>

69
00:03:32,446 --> 00:03:34,625
<i>...and put them in the game.</i>

70
00:03:35,728 --> 00:03:39,398
<i>And let's see what happens.</i>

71
00:03:45,040 --> 00:03:47,600
The generation indie game
developers are coming from,

72
00:03:47,876 --> 00:03:49,893
and I'm part of this generation also,

73
00:03:50,061 --> 00:03:53,773
we're the first generation that
grew up with video games.

74
00:03:53,960 --> 00:03:57,533
But not as
an active purchasing choice.

75
00:03:57,923 --> 00:04:00,060
Since I was part of
that generation...

76
00:04:00,228 --> 00:04:01,865
I feel an ownership of it.

77
00:04:02,035 --> 00:04:03,533
Games are mine.

78
00:04:03,703 --> 00:04:08,161
For anyone that grew up
after 1975; 1980 or so...

79
00:04:08,333 --> 00:04:10,850
...we were the first generation
to grow up with our parents

80
00:04:11,026 --> 00:04:12,873
...giving us games.
And for us to grow up with games...

81
00:04:13,210 --> 00:04:15,991
...as a natural, and relevant part of
our everyday existence.

82
00:04:16,161 --> 00:04:17,880
This is not a
weird kid activity for me.

83
00:04:18,048 --> 00:04:21,175
This is not like
some strange nerdy pastime.

84
00:04:21,343 --> 00:04:23,278
This has been a part of my life.

85
00:04:23,448 --> 00:04:24,345
There's been a tendency...

86
00:04:24,513 --> 00:04:26,723
...over the past couple decades in
mainstream games...

87
00:04:26,891 --> 00:04:29,471
...to make everything bigger
and more realistic.

88
00:04:30,186 --> 00:04:32,848
To 'Amp Up'
everything.

89
00:04:33,648 --> 00:04:35,253
[GUS]
Big games have other goals.

90
00:04:35,421 --> 00:04:36,440
They want to entertain you.

91
00:04:36,608 --> 00:04:40,816
They want to get 10 million people
playing at the same time.

92
00:04:40,840 --> 00:04:42,901
But with Indie Games,
it's often 1 person

93
00:04:43,055 --> 00:04:44,908
Who says:
I want a game to be like this.

94
00:04:45,203 --> 00:04:48,828
I want a game to be about
this special thing.

95
00:04:49,068 --> 00:04:52,398
Independent games are any game
that a small team...

96
00:04:52,566 --> 00:04:55,708
...or individual worked on
to their own vision.

97
00:04:55,878 --> 00:04:58,808
Something that they felt like making,
coding and finishing.

98
00:04:59,441 --> 00:05:01,633
The major thing that made
this possible...

99
00:05:01,801 --> 00:05:04,308
...is the rise of
digital distribution.

100
00:05:04,536 --> 00:05:08,263
Retailers used to have
a lot of power...

101
00:05:08,431 --> 00:05:10,543
...over every game creation company.

102
00:05:10,711 --> 00:05:14,228
Because that was
the only way to sell games.

103
00:05:14,440 --> 00:05:18,063
Nobody was willing to start
distributing games digitally.

104
00:05:18,231 --> 00:05:20,358
Because WalMart would get upset
at them.

105
00:05:20,530 --> 00:05:23,151
And take their products off the shelf.
And nothing would happen.

106
00:05:23,326 --> 00:05:25,905
But Valve changed that,
when they came out with Steam.

107
00:05:26,080 --> 00:05:29,636
They had no loyalties to retail.
So they just did it.

108
00:05:29,641 --> 00:05:32,955
After that everyone else said:
'Well, we have to compete with them'

109
00:05:33,250 --> 00:05:36,626
And there was this whole flood of:
XBox Live Arcade...

110
00:05:36,795 --> 00:05:38,178
...Playstation network...

111
00:05:38,348 --> 00:05:40,873
...and WiiWare followed suit.

112
00:05:42,425 --> 00:05:46,543
2008 was the first year that
indie games started to do really well.

113
00:05:46,711 --> 00:05:48,888
Audiosurf came out on Steam.

114
00:05:49,473 --> 00:05:50,835
Then Castle Crashers...

115
00:05:51,008 --> 00:05:52,931
...and Braid and World of Goo.

116
00:05:53,101 --> 00:05:55,098
Osmos did really well in 2009, 2010.

117
00:05:55,961 --> 00:06:00,731
Then Limbo came out and broke records.

118
00:06:00,901 --> 00:06:03,010
And Minecraft came out as well-

119
00:06:03,178 --> 00:06:06,261
Actually, it came out much earlier,
but then it really built up...

120
00:06:06,430 --> 00:06:08,073
...and blew those records away.

121
00:06:08,243 --> 00:06:09,448
And when we're talking about
'really well' ...

122
00:06:09,618 --> 00:06:13,120
...we're talking about
millions of dollars in revenue.

123
00:06:13,443 --> 00:06:16,833
So for teams of 200,
millions of dollars...

124
00:06:17,005 --> 00:06:19,510
...doesn't really count for much.

125
00:06:19,678 --> 00:06:21,755
But for a team of 2, 3 people...

126
00:06:21,926 --> 00:06:24,168
... that's really significant money.

